First of all, if we build with ``` [input_a, input_b, res]```, the order of the input to the host side of the function, is the same(input_a, input_b, res), so we do not need fixed_order_args to store the original order information in the build (we already are).

The reason that the device side of the argument is different is that the order can be permutated determined when we split between host and device. This need to be addressed properly by ordering argument in the SplitDeviceCode pass. However, there is no strictly one to one mapping. Consider the following case, which can be generated by adding two tensors together(with the same length).

```c
void device_func(void* data1, void* data2, int n) {
}

void host_func(DLTensor* x1, DLTensor*x2) {
  void* ptr1 = x1->data;
  void* ptr2 = x2->data;
  int n = x1->shape[0];
  int n2 = x2->shape[0];
  assert(n == n2);
  device_func(ptr1, ptr2, n);
}
```

You can find that the signature in device_func does not directly correspond to the arguments in the host_func. In the best case, we can define a rule, for example, ptr1 traces back to x1, ptr2 traces back to x2, and we order them as ptr1 and ptr2, but how should we order n is an interesting question.

